This is a quick perl script to scan through a gcode file and figure out how much filament will be required.
It reads all of the "E" moves and adds them up each time they get reset to 0.
This will only work with absolute moves, not relative moves. I did a 5 hour print and weighed it. The script said it should way 48.167 g. My kitchen scale said it weight 50 g.
Pretty good!

After downloading this script you may have to make it executable (chmod gou+x filament_length.pl) To use it just pipe the gcode file through the perl script: cat mygcodefile.gcode | ./filament_length.pl (replace the ./ with whatever the path is to the script) or, you can specify the file on the command line like this: ./filament_length.pl -f filename.gcode you can also specify the density (in g/cc) and size of the filament (in mm) ./filament_length.pl -d 1.25 -s 2.75 -f filename.gcode You can include or omit any of the command switches you like, it reads from stdin if you omit the filename and a density of 1.05 and diameter of 1.75 if you omit them.
The density of ABS is around 1.05 g/cc, PLA should be around 1.25 g/cc It will produce a report like the following: Cross sectional area of filament: 0.0240527984375 cm^2 macbookpro:~ jag$ ./filament_length.pl -d 1.25 -f ~/Dropbox/repg\ files/Dreidel03.gcode
Filament diameter is 1.75 mm
Filament density is 1.25 g/cc
Cross sectional area of filament: 0.0240527984375 cm^2 Total filament: 738.936 cm
Volume: 17.773 cc
Weight: 22.217 g

description.text: Here's a handy little cardboard spool you can use for your MakerBot filament. I designed it for a thicker cardboard than pictured, but all I had around when I was inspired were some pizza boxes. As posted on my blog http://charlespax.wordpress.com/2010/01/08/cardboard-spool/ See it in action as part of the future Bowden filament drive box http://charlespax.com/2010/01/26/makerbot-filament-box-and-drive-mechanism/ The latest version can be found in subversion at http://svn.makerbot.com/users/charles/bowden/ . EDIT 2010-03-21: I added a divider to the files. Thanks, Kevin. I also decreased the size of the hole that secures the filament to better grab the it.

Cut out two flanges and one barrel. Bend the barrel so it curls and feed it into one of the flanges. Fold the tabs back into the flange through the smaller holes. Packing tape helps to hold them in place.
Now you'll have a top hat crown thing. Place your filament roll over the barrel and put on the other flange. Again, tape helps.
A 10 mm shaft through the arbor hole and you're ready to print. Well, you'll probably want some sort of mount for this. It's coming...

comments.text: If you don't have access to a laser cutter, you might want to look up one of your local corrugated board suppliers or a box manufacturer. Most plants have a designer on staff with a cutting table. A cutting table can cut from DXF files with minor conversion, or directly from an HPG or ACS file. If the designer is a bit of geek (very likely), he or she may cut it for you for free from scrap stock if you let them use the file how they want.

title: SD card holder insert for film canisters

description.text:
Insert for 35mm film canisters that can hold up to six SD memory cards. If you shoot digital but still feel some nostalgia for the old film days, this is for you. Store your memory cards waterproof and with style.

On the bottom, the insert has a socket for a 18mm spring (I used this one), so it will raise upon opening the canister. Works without the spring too, but will be less comfortable when taking out cards.

Should work with all 35mm film canisters that have an inner diameter of 30-31mm and a inner load height of 44mm. These measures are quite standard, but there are some canisters which are smaller and won't take the insert.

description.text:
Dingo_aus did a great job of transforming the MeArm 4.0 into a printable version.

However, I found that the files are not quiet friendly for my Printer.
So I modify them for better result.

Thing I did include :

  • Introduce a round BasePanel (BasePanel_MG90_Round.STL)
    -- Designed for TowerPro MG90 servo, may works for others
    -- Significantly decrease the gap between the rotation part
  • Introduce a Wedged Bucket part (ServoBucket_Wedged.stl)
    -- For more tolerance on first layer height
  • Introduce a Wedged Claw Servo Bucket part (mearm_part8_Changed_v2.STL)
    -- For more tolerance on first layer height
  • Lay-down the original parts to print at a 20cm x 20 cm bed.

The Part 7 of Dingo_aus's integrated model are not included because 20cm x 20 cm print bed can print the motherboard (Part 26) in one piece.

description.text:
Overview

This grabber comes from
The Parametric Grabber.

I found the hand as it was designed was too small so set about making it bigger.

I increased it by 133% which allowed me to use a 21.5mm PVC pipe as the "arm" / tube.
The pipe is common in most countries:
UK, Australia, USA (1/2" SCH-40)

This grabber has a new "toy" trigger handle as the original was too had for the kids, so I set about (18 months later) to make a simpler trigger style handle and this is the result!.

The trigger rotates a cog which is the string puller. All 4 fingers work in unison, not independent.

Parts Required

  • Strong non stretch fishing line
  • Strong Thin elastic (I got some from the local sewing shop)
  • Filament to use for the "joint" bolts
  • 2x 20 - 30mm M4 Bolts (they form the hinge pins for the handle)

Assembly & Print Notes

  • The finger in this model has the 3d support strictures already added (just as I printed it 18 months back).
  • The handle can be glued closed. I have not done that yet.
  • I have all parts in sketchup if anyone wants them
  • The edges of the handle are 90˚ sharp. (perhaps they need a softer edge)
  • Be SUPER carefule with the "hand" square edges on the palm. We had one kid with a bleeding head because of it :-)
  • Tieing the fishing line tight is tricky. Get the elastic super strong is my advice.

title: Emax Nighthawk 200 Multi-Purpose Runcam2 / Mobius Mount
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
NOTE: If you don't have a Loc8tor, please try this successor.

This is a 25° angled mount for a Mobius/Runcam2-type action cam designed to fit an Emax Nighthawk 200 frame. It's designed to be sturdy, light, and make the best possible use of space by integrating additional features - hence 'multi-purpose'. My ABS print weighs 10 g.

The real-life pics of this mount are taken from earlier prototypes, features have been added or changed since. The download file is always the newest version only.

Features:

  • cam to be strapped down with a velcro lock strap (16-20 mm width, e.g. a small Scorpion Strap)
  • cam is kept from sliding out in front
  • follows original front board outline exactly, uses original screws
  • houses a Loc8tor Tag between strap and cam (lenticular version)
  • houses a Lemon Satellite or similar (need to decase if used with Loc8tor)
  • mounts antenna tubes (dia 3.3 mm or fit with shrink tubes/duct tape)
  • mounts an LED headlight (remove plastic rear, seal and fit into place with shrink tubes)

If you would like different angles or other modifications, please feel free to contact me and I'll try my best to help you out. I appreciate any comments and suggestions.

Change history:

UPDATE 16-08-31: This Thing is now more or less obsolete, I'm not developing it any further, just keeping it in the archive. Use this successor instead - I'm through with this rubbish Loc8tor stuff.

UPDATE 16-06-01: Minor refinements:

  • Enlarged the holes for the antennas to a nominal Ø3.6 mm because they came out too small in print and I had to ream them, destroying the inner stopper ledge in the process.
  • Added a ledge in front to keep the cam from sliding out.
  • Enlarged the width of the lock strap slot.

UPDATE 16-05-13: I uploaded an improved version of the mount. I did away with the non-functional ziptie stuff and made support holes for real antenna tubes Ø3.3 mm. The front looks a bit different now, the cam support was actually too long and is now made to blend in better with the side plate design of the frame. While playing around with the prototype, we also came upon the idea of integrating one of the LED spots we had at hand - just for kicks.

UPDATE 16-05-11: I had a prototype printed by a local hub in 50 micron ABS on a Zortrax M200. It was as expensive as it is beautiful, and it seems pretty much indestructible to me - but then I have to admit it was printed with quite massive settings, too. I'll spoil you with some pics.
Anyway, the antenna mount by the side slots did not turn out as intended. Zipties won't grip (who has ever heard a thing like this?!?), so we ended up having to drill two other holes into it. I am going to rework and update this Thing in the next few days and adjust some of the features... maybe even add one. :)
If you are intending to print it, you won't regret waiting a bit. I want this to be the ultimate multi-purpose mount for this frame. Thank you for your patience!

Flying the ring

The airfoil is designed to keep the center of lift on or near the disk's center of gravity. If the center of lift is forward of the CG the disk will gyroscopically precess left for a right handed (CW rotation) throw. If the center of lift is aft of the CG the disk will precess right for a right handed throw. The opposite is true for a left handed throw (CCW rotation).

This ring is very light and so does not have the range of a heavier commercial ring like the Aerobie. However it can travel straight for a good distance. At the very end of its flight the prototype tends to drop of to the left. I've had good success launching it strongly with a slight tilt to the right and up (I'm right handed so it spins CW for me).

A UV exposure box is an extremely useful piece to make PCBs.

I have searched and found that they are too big and too expensive for my uses. In addition, all the devices require an external power sorce.

Thereupon I decided to build one that fits better on my needs.

My requirements:
-Compact dimensions
-USB charging
-Long battery runtime
-No buttons or knobs
-Very simple use

So I built a box, with which you can exposure up to 184 PCBs on a single charge!

You need to solder, drill a PCB, print the files, programm an Arduino or a ATTiny and
screw everything together.

Detailed instructions can be found on instructables:
http://www.instructables.com/id/PCB-UV-Exposure-Unit/

I've designed all parts in Google SketchUp.

As a guide, I had all components and especially the glass sheet.

The main body part is cut in half, because my small printer has a plate with only 150 x 150mm.

Then I export the STL files, slice and print them on my printer.

title: Improved Replacement Housing for Sandisk CZ80 USB 3.0 Drive

description.text:
Annoyed with the otherwise excellent Sandisk CZ80 retracting as you insert it into the computer? Why not replace the housing with a 3D printed one!

This thing has a few options: print it yourself and glue together, OR, slice the "oneshot" file, and insert a pause at 5mm z-height, where you can insert the USB completely, and then have the print resume, encapsulating the USB permanently without needing clips or adhesives!

Features thin wall to allow the read/write LED light to shine through, as well as internal cutouts to support the PCB components of varying sizes.

Designs with and without a keyring loop included. :-)

More info at my blog: http://samuelpinches.com.au/3d-printer/encapsulated-sandisk-cz80/
